>Eoforheard</i> (from <i>eofor</i> ‘boar’ + <i>heard</i> ‘hardy, brave’), but many bearers of this name were undoubtedly Normans, who took it from the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Eburhard</i>, <i>Everhard</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":8,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":102,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":111,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Everard was born in 1447, in Chediston, Suffolk, England, his father, John Everard Sr., was 28 and his mother, Mrs. Everard, was 24. He married Margaret Dale about 1472, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1447–":"1447–Surnud","1447–Male":"1447–Surnud","1451–Female":"1451–Surnud","1473–1561":"1473–1561","1419–Male":"1419–Surnud","1423–Female":"1423–Surnud","Abt 1472":"umbes 1472","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1473":"1473","1561":"1561","1451":"1451","Abt 1444":"umbes 1444","1419":"1419","1549":"1549","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England","Of, Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Shanfield, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1447–":"1447–Kuollut","1447–Male":"1447–Kuollut","1451–Female":"1451–Kuollut","1473–1561":"1473–1561","1419–Male":"1419–Kuollut","1423–Female":"1423–Kuollut","Abt 1472":"noin 1472","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1473":"1473","1561":"1561","1451":"1451","Abt 1444":"noin 1444","1419":"1419","1549":"1549","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, England","Of, Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of, Shanfield, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1447–":"1447–Décédé","1447–Male":"1447–Décédé","1451–Female":"1451–Décédée","1473–1561":"1473–1561","1419–Male":"1419–Décédé","1423–Female":"1423–Décédée","Abt 1472":"environ 1472","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1473":"1473","1561":"1561","1451":"1451","Abt 1444":"environ 1444","1419":"1419","1549":"1549","Chediston, Suffolk, England":"Chediston, Suffolk, Angleterre","Of, Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Of, Shanfield, S